Problem C1: Go= ld Mine - Chapter 1
21 points

  • My SubmissionsMy Submissions
  • SolutionS= olution
Note: This problem shares similarities w= ith Chapter 2. The solution to either c= hapter may help with solving the other, so please consider reading both fir= st.
Just like logging, mining is a= key industry in Canada's primary sector. Prospectors use geological tools = to find ore deposits, then drill, a= nd blast to excavate a system of underground tunnels for access to the = ores.
Minerva is a contract miner who spends her days extracting gold = ore from underground mines across Ontario. One particular gold mine she's c= ontracting for consists of NN<= /math>N underground caves, numbered from 111<= /span> to NNN, with cave 111 having an exit to the surface. There are also N=E2=88=921N - 1= N=E2=88=921 tunnels running among the caves, the ii= <= span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.65952em;">ith of which= allows one to travel in either direction between caves <= semantics>AiA_iAi=E2= =80=8B and BiB_i<= /span>Bi= =E2=80=8B= . Each cave is reachable from= cave 111 by a sequence of these tunnels.=
Cave = iii is known to contain CiC_iCi=E2=80=8B<= /span> ounces of gold ore. With her trusty dump truck, Minerv= a plans to drive underground starting in cave = 11= 1, co= llect as much gold ore as possible, and exit back to the surface through ca= ve 111.
There's just one issue: the tunnels ar= e highly unstable, and will cave in after Minerva drives through them. Ther= efore, she is only able to traverse each tunnel at most once. Fortunately, = the caves themselves are reinforced with pillars and will never collapse = =E2=80=94 she may visit each cave any number of times (though she can only = collect its gold ore at most once).
This safety measure may limit m= obility. Thankfully, Minerva's truck is also equipped to be a drill rig. As= she travels through the system of caves, she may at any point use it to tr= avel from her current cave to any other cave = by drilling a new tunnel. In this chapter, the= rig only has the energy to drill at most one such tunnel. Unfortunately, t= his new tunnel will be just as unstable as the existing ones =E2=80=94 Mine= rva will only dare travel through it once.
Please help Minerva dete= rmine the maximum weight of gold ore that can be collected if she begins in= cave 111, spends any amount of time exploring the mine= (traveling through tunnels, drilling at most one new tunnel, and collectin= g ore from any visited caves), and end up once again in cave = 111.

Constraints

<= div data-offset-key=3D"b55ps-0-0" class=3D"_1mf _1mj">= 1=E2=89=A4T=E2=89=A4351 \le T \le 351=E2=89=A4T=E2=89=A435 1=E2=89=A4N=E2=89=A4501 \le N \le 501=E2=89=A4N= =E2=89=A450 0=E2=89=A4C<= /mi>i=E2=89=A420,000,0000 \le C_i \le 20{,}000{,}0000=E2= =89=A4C<= /span>i=E2=80= =8B=E2= =89=A42,000,0= 00 1=E2=89=A4A<= /mi>i,Bi=E2=89=A4N1 \le A_i, B_i \le N1=E2=89=A4Ai=E2=80=8B,B<= /span>i=E2=80= =8B=E2= =89=A4N
The sum of = NN<= /semantics>N across all mines is at most 1,0001{,}000= 1,000= .

Input

Input begins with an intege= r TTT, the number = of mines that Minerva is contracted to work. For each mine, there is first = a line containing the single integer NNN<= /span>. Then, there is a second line containing <= math>NNN space-separated integers, C1..NC_{1..N}= <= span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.68333em;">C1..N=E2=80=8B. Then, N=E2=88=921N - 1N=E2=88=921 l= ines follow, the = iiith of which contains the space-sep= arated integers <= span class=3D"katex-mathml">AiA_i= <= span class=3D"strut" style=3D"height: 0.68333em;">A= i<= /span>=E2=80=8B= and = BiB_= iB= i=E2=80=8B= .

Output

For the iiith mine, = output a line containing "Case #i: " followed= by a single integer, the maximum weight of gold ore (in ounces) that Miner= va can collect before leaving the mine.

Sample Explanation

The first mine looks as follows:
It's possible to visit both caves (collecting 303030 ounces of ore) and then retur= n to cave 111, for example by taking the tunnel from ca= ve 111 to cave = 222<= span data-offset-key=3D"cdtf2-8-0"> and then drill= ing a tunnel back to cave 11<= /math>1.
The second mi= ne looks as follows:
<= /div>
It's p= ossible to end up with the ore from all = 44<= /semantics>4 caves, for = example by taking the tunnel to cave 333<= span data-offset-key=3D"76aqs-4-0">, drilling to c= ave 444, and then taking tunnels to cave = 222 followed by cave 1<= /mrow>1= 1.
The third = mine looks as follows:
It's po= ssible to end up with 3<= annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">3= 3 ounces of ore, but Minerva ca= nnot collect all = 444 ounces while still returning to ca= ve 111 and only drilling one tunnel.
